<DOC><DOCNO> AP890517-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-17-89 1021EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-People-Hahn-Bakker     05-17 0288</FIRST><SECOND>PM-People-Hahn-Bakker,0297</SECOND><HEAD>Jessica Hahn Collects Pledges to Try to Lure Bakker to Meet Her</HEAD><DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jessica Hahn, the former secretary whosesexual liaison with Jim Bakker crumbled his PTL ministry, appearedon a radio broadcast today near his ministry and challenged him toa meeting.   ``I don't want anything sloppy,'' she said on WBJW's ``BreakfastBunch'' talk show, which was being broadcast from a bar a fewhundred feet from Bakker's new ministry.   ``It's never been done to have Jim Bakker and me set down andtell our story,'' she said. ``I just want the healing process tostart.   ``I'm not afraid of a confrontation. I think you are,'' shesaid, addressing Bakker. ``Come out here for five minutes,one-on-one.''   It couldn't immediately be learned if Bakker was listening tothe program. The Bakkers said Tuesday they would delay the dailytaping of their ``Jim and Tammy'' show until late this afternoon toavoid Ms. Hahn and the hoopla surrounding her.   Ms. Hahn was broadcasting from the Sports Page, a bar across theparking lot from the new television ministry Jim and Tammy Bakkerset up in a nearly abandoned shopping mall in southwest Orlando.   Tom Hoof, promotions manager for WBJW-FM and WBJW-AM in WinterPark, had said Tuesday the station didn't want a confrontation, buttoday his morning show co-hosts joined Ms. Hahn in taking telephonepledges for Bakker's new ministry and inviting him to pick up themoney.   ``We'll give you a check,'' Ms. Hahn said. ``I just want to talkto you for about two seconds.''   By 8:15 a.m. they had pledges for $1,163, including donations bythe station itself.   Hoof wouldn't say what Hahn is being paid for the appearance.</TEXT></DOC>